                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>What I don't understand is how this fits in with the "starvation mode" your body supposedly goes into when it doesn't think it's getting enough calories - in other words, it hangs on to what it has and refuses to let you lose weight. At what point does the amount you eat less than before allow you to get lighter and at what point does your body refuse to cooperate? It's all so arcane. </p><p>There was one week last month when I ran a total of about 50 miles, ate muesli for breakfast, salad for lunch and no (or very limited) carbs at night - and no naughty snacks at all - and lost not a single gram of weight. When I whined about this to a dietician friend of mine she chuckled and said "ah, it's because you're not eating enough. Eat more and the weight will come off". It all seemed (a) bizarre and (b) UNFAIR. Waaahh, etc.</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
				<li class="comment-tools">
