			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-7710727">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/site_furniture/2010/09/01/no-user-image.gif" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/trevorgleet" title="User profile page">trevorgleet</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">19 September 2010 1:46AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>The studies quoted seem to suggest that institutionalised / commodified / masochistic forms of exercise such as 'working out' in gyms don't help people lose weight because they 'compensate' by eating more and/or exercising less the rest of the time.  But the 'good news' bit at the end suggests that gentle pleasurable exercise such as walking does help because it doesn't trigger the compensations.</p><p>Sounds plausible.  Doing repetitive meaningless physical jerks with weird apparatus in enclosed spaces surrounded by other vile bodies in ritual clothing must be so revolting and demeaning that it's not surprising people need to bribe themselves with comfort food to do it.  Whereas walking or cycling in the open, engaging vividly with one's surroundings, gives feelings of wellbeing, contentment and control of one's life which surely make it easier to forego excessive and unhealthy foods.  And doesn't gentle regular 'background' exercise helps keep metabolism up, burning off excess food, in a way that the occasional violent convulsion doesn't?</p><p>If so, there are clear but radical implications for policy.  Forget about organised sport and commercially packaged exercise, just make it easy and attractive for most people do some walking and cycling as part of their daily routine.</p><p>'Solutions are elsewhere', as Milan Kundera could have said.  Maybe car restraint and attractive safe streets and public spaces could do more for fitness and healthy weights than special sporting and excercise facilities.</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
