			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-7710929">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/site_furniture/2010/09/01/no-user-image.gif" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/hieros" title="User profile page">hieros</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">19 September 2010 3:16AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>this is my experience too <b>bree67</b>, something happens to my taste buds and attitude to food when i do exercise, so i just want to eat fresher nourishing food ..</p><p>Take a look at the countries in the world and see where most of the obesity is ...........sedentary lifestyles and greed dominate the west !<br> exercise may not be the only answer, but it helps a hell of a lot.</p><p>If you've ever been to usa, and look at the plates of food they serve in restaurants, any idiot can see that it will stuff you to the gills, and blow you up into a michelin man .....people stuff themselves because they feel 'empty', this is not to do with hunger, but a long-established crisis of values. Food, alcohol, drugs, porn are all used to overstimulate the senses ( and deaden them by turn ) so that people feel they are getting more life.</p><p>I also find that if i go to a 'good' restaurant, or make a nice dish myself (which can be inexpensive), I want to eat less. There is nothing worse than eating something nice, then ruining it by feelings of discomfort from stuffing !</p><p>There is an interesting article in 'scientific american mind' recently, looking at how we frame things, and whether we succeed, or not. Those who framed their goals, as ' I will', rather than "will I?', achieved less. There is a paradoxical effect here, which we already knew about, but its good to see the research ...... We know that when we try too hard, we often fail.  When we use the 'I will' frame, the driving force, is avoiding guilt and shame from NOT doing what we set out to do. This is less of a driving force, than connecting with our own 'want', and framing it as 'will i'. ..... if that makes sense</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
