			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-7710940">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/site_furniture/2010/09/01/no-user-image.gif" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/together" title="User profile page">together</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">19 September 2010 3:26AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>YummieMummie - muscley/toned through exercise is fine if you keep it up for the rest of your life. If you use exercise as the means of controlling your weight you are not acknowledging the cause of your problem. Weight gain is a result of eating too much, not a result of lack of exercise. Treat the cause, not the symptom. Eat less. Simple as that. Exercise is necessary for other health benefits but not as a cure for over-eating. And it is worth remembering that the unnecessary extra muscle you build up to cope with the unnatural gym regime will turn to fat as soon as the regime is broken. Eat what you need to maintain your weight only and incorporate exercise into your normal daily activities - if you are walking, walk quickly, use the stairs, not the elevator, park at the furthest side of the superstore car park, not nearest to the entrance.</p>
						
					</div>
