                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<blockquote><p>From StairMasters to kettlebells, Rosemary Conley to Natalie Cassidy, we understand and expect that getting in shape is going to require serious effort on our part – and the reverse is true, too, that we expect exercise to pay back the hours of boring, sweaty graft with a leaner, lighter body.</p></blockquote><p>You sit if front of the TV for hours on end watching Spiderman 2 for the 5th time, and you're not bored; you go for a brisk 30 min jog in the park and you're bored to death. What's clearly the issue here is not boredom but sloth. Everything in life is attitude, you think something is going to be boring and ta daa it's boring. </p><p>Tho exercise is not as effective a weight-reduction strategy as simply eating less, getting off your ass is absolutely vital to maintain one's health and feeling of well-being; it's also essential for the over-50 crowd to fight off the debilitating effects of age.  I go through on-again-off-again phases of exercising, what always starts me moving again is the numbing torpor that comes with chronic inactivity.</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
