			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-7711267">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/site_furniture/2010/09/01/no-user-image.gif" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/jmpg" title="User profile page">jmpg</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">19 September 2010 6:57AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>"To burn off an extra 500 calories is typically an extra two hours of cycling"<br>This is entirely inconsistent with even the most pessimistic advice which is generally available about the amount of calories which can be burned through aerobic exercise such as cycling. It would only be true if you already weighed less than 9 stone and were cycling at about walking speed. For example see http://www.caloriecounter.co.uk/calories-burnt-by-exercise/, according to which two hours of cycling would burn off over 2000 calories (a result much more consistent with my own experience of losing weight largely through cycling) for an average person. <br>The same could be said for the comments about running from Leeds to Nottingham. Running from Leeds to Nottingham very slowly if you're already at a low weight wouldn't burn off that much extra weight, but running daily, fairly fast, for an hour will burn several pounds per week off most people.  <br>The list of exercises which is given at the end of the article is completely misleading, as it mainly refers to forms of exercise which are well known to be of little value in burning calories, and it mainly gives the calories burned in very short spaces of time. Of course playing frisbee for half an hour a day isn't going to get you thin - nobody ever believed that it would. <br>The article seems to deal with these inconsistencies by implying that anyone who actually exercises vigorously each day has the training schedule of an olympic athlete. This is just sensationalist nonsense. For most people who currently take no regular aerobic exercise, switching to something like a daily cycling commute, 30 minutes each way, will have a significant effect on the amount of calrcaloriesoies they burn through exercise per week, which will have a direct impact on their weight provided they don't make up the calories by eating more.</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
