			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-7711498">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/site_furniture/2010/09/01/no-user-image.gif" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/Imlessbiasedthanyou2" title="User profile page">Imlessbiasedthanyou2</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">19 September 2010 8:14AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>"studies "have demonstrated no or modest weight loss with exercise alone" and that "an exercise regimen… is unlikely to result in short-term weight loss beyond what is achieved with dietary change."</p><p>You don't really need to read any more after this. This isn't a new finding then really, is it?</p><p> I agree with another poster who said that the headline is misleading, in that it implies that excercise cannot lead to weight loss, when as I suspected, it is admitted very quickly in the piece that what the study actually said was exercise <i>alone </i>is unikely to lead to significant weight loss. </p><p>Tell us something we don't know. As for those who do experience weight loss without dietary change, that's great, we all have different metabolisms, but you will not be a majority. </p><p>Also (and I am not an expert, just a reasonably well informed member of the community), if you lose weight through <i>dietary change </i>alone, this is not necessarily making you more healthy overall. Excercise combined with a good diet means you are fit externally and internally, with the muscles, organs and mind all getting what they need.</p>
						
