			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-7711803">
				
				<li class="comment-author" >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                

<img class="author-profile-picture" src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/site_furniture/2010/09/01/no-user-image.gif" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/BennyBlanco" title="User profile page">BennyBlanco</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">19 September 2010 9:15AM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<blockquote><p>Church identified the problem and called it "compensation": those who exercised cancelled out the calories they had burned by eating more, generally as a form of self-reward. The post-workout pastry to celebrate a job well done – or even a few pieces of fruit to satisfy their stimulated appetites – undid their good work.</p></blockquote><p>So the study didn't work because the women involved were stupid. And one can probably infer that if they <i>hadn't</i> snacked and overcompensated, then they <i>would</i> have lost weight, can't you?</p><p>I'd like to do a study. I would take two identical twins who weigh the same and have the same body composition. Over the course of a week I would put one of them in front of the tv and have someone bring them happy meals. They wouldn't have to move. The other twin I would make run (at gunpoint if necessary) between the various different Maccas to get their happy meals (eaten at exactly the same time), only stopping to sleep at night and go to the toilet. My hypothesis is the running twin will lose weight, and the sedentary twin will gain weight, a statistically significant weight difference with a p value of &lt;0.0005.</p><p>Expect my results to be published in the Lancet in the coming years. This is only a pilot study of course, numbers will be far to small to draw any meaningful conclusions, but should lead to funding (possibly from a certain fast food chain) for a population-based study.</p>
						
					</div>
