					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>together - you do know that fat and muscle are different type of cells?  Muscle can't turn into fat...  what does tend to happen is that people stop exercising but continue eating as if they were, the muscles shrink back to their pre-exercise level since they're not being used and because there's now a calorie overload, the fat cells get bigger.</p><p>Overall, this isn't telling us much new.  The ones who exercised also appeared to increase their calorie intake so they didn't lose weight - it would be interesting to know if their cardiovascular health improved and what kind of exercise it was - soulless pounding on a treadmill or fun group activiities or outdoors?</p><p>I can't honestly believe the recommendation to skip a meal every day for a week rather than go and do some exercise to burn off 500 calories - which incidentally, unless you cycle with stabilisers isn't going to take you 2 hours!</p>
						
